        // ── Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided (Article) ─────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided",
            Slug = "vendors-create-quick-vs-guided",
            Summary = "The New Vendor setup choice: when to use Quick add versus the 5-step Guided setup wizard, and what each path captures.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/vendors","/vendors/new"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","procurement","onboarding"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Creating a Vendor: Quick vs Guided\n\nClicking **+ New Vendor** on the Vendors page no longer drops you straight into a form — it opens a small **window** that asks *how* you want to set up the vendor. There are two paths, and choosing the right one saves rework later.\n\n### The choice window\n\nThe window shows two cards:\n\n- **Quick add** (badged *Fast*) — \"Just the essentials — company name and basic contact. Flesh out the rest later.\" This is the dominant, everyday path.\n- **Guided setup** — \"Step-by-step for strategic or approved vendors — classification, address, terms, and the parts they supply.\"\n\nClick a card to choose; the **Cancel** button at the bottom backs out without creating anything.\n\n### Quick add — the everyday path\n\nQuick add opens the flat vendor dialog. The only required field is **Company Name**; contact name, email, phone, address, payment terms, and notes are all optional and can be filled in later. Use Quick add when:\n\n- You just need the vendor to exist so you can put it on a purchase order.\n- It is a one-off or low-volume transactional supplier.\n- You will enrich the record later (or let an accounting sync fill in the details).\n\nThe vendor is created immediately and becomes available in PO vendor dropdowns. You can always open the vendor later and add an address, terms, or catalog parts.\n\n### Guided setup — for strategic / approved vendors\n\nChoosing **Guided setup** opens a step-by-step wizard (the same style used for Parts). It's worth the extra effort for strategic suppliers, approved vendors, or any vendor whose address, terms, and supplied parts you want captured up front. The wizard walks five steps:\n\n1. **Identity** *(required)* — Company name, contact name, email, and phone. This step is what actually creates the vendor, so company name is required here. Until you finish it, nothing is saved.\n2. **Address** *(optional)* — Street, city, state, ZIP, and country for the vendor's billing and shipping address.\n3. **Terms** *(optional)* — Payment terms (Net 30, and so on) and related billing settings.\n4. **Supply Items** *(optional)* — A reminder step. You add the parts this vendor supplies — along with their approval, preferred, and pricing settings — on the vendor's **Catalog** tab after the vendor exists, rather than entering them all here.\n5. **Review** *(required)* — A final summary; confirm to finish.\n\n### Express vs Guided mode inside the wizard\n\nThe wizard has two modes you can switch between. *Guided* mode shows one step at a time with the reasoning available in a side panel; *Express* mode puts the optional steps on a single screen for people who already know what they're entering. Both modes cover the same steps and the same required stops (Identity and Review).\n\n### Save and come back later\n\nThe wizard remembers where you are. Once the Identity step has created the vendor, you can bookmark or share the page and pick up a half-finished setup right where you left off.\n\n### Which should I pick?\n\n| Situation | Path |\n|---|---|\n| Need the vendor on a PO right now | Quick add |\n| One-off or low-volume supplier | Quick add |\n| Strategic / sole-source / AVL partner | Guided setup |\n| You want address + terms + supplied parts captured up front | Guided setup |\n| Importing many vendor-supplied parts | Guided setup, then bulk CSV import on the Catalog tab |\n\nThere is no \"convert from lead\" path for vendors (leads become customers, not suppliers), so the choice is two-way rather than three-way.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Vendor Catalog & AVL (Article) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
