            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":7,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"vc1","text":"You click + New Vendor to add a strategic, sole-source supplier and want to capture its address, payment terms, and the parts it supplies up front. Which path should you choose?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Quick add — it captures everything in one flat form"},{"id":"b","text":"Guided setup — the 5-step wizard for strategic or approved vendors","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Convert from Lead — promote the supplier lead to a vendor"},{"id":"d","text":"There is no choice; New Vendor always opens the same form"}],"explanation":"New Vendor lets you choose Quick add (essentials only, fastest) or Guided setup. For a strategic or approved (AVL) supplier where you want classification, address, terms, and supplied parts captured up front, choose Guided setup — it opens the 5-step wizard (Identity, Address, Terms, Supply Items, Review). There is no convert-from-lead path for vendors."},{"id":"vc2","text":"In the Guided vendor wizard, which step actually creates the vendor record, and is therefore required?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Address"},{"id":"b","text":"Terms"},{"id":"c","text":"Identity (company name + contact)","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Supply Items"}],"explanation":"The Identity step (company name, contact name, email, phone) creates the vendor record, so company name is required there. Until Identity is completed, nothing is saved. Address, Terms, and Supply Items are optional; Review is the required final confirmation."},{"id":"vc3","text":"On a vendor's Catalog tab, what does the Approved (green check) flag on a supplied part represent?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The vendor-part has been synced from QuickBooks"},{"id":"b","text":"The vendor is cleared to supply this part — the Approved Vendor List (AVL) marker","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The part has at least one price tier defined"},{"id":"d","text":"The purchase order for this part has been approved"}],"explanation":"The Approved toggle is the Approved Vendor List (AVL) marker: this vendor is qualified/cleared to supply this part. Approved rows show a green check; un-approved rows show a blocked icon. Purchasing uses it to steer buyers toward qualified sources. It is unrelated to accounting sync, pricing, or PO approval."},{"id":"vc4","text":"You set the Preferred (star) flag on Vendor A for Part X. Vendor B was previously the preferred source for Part X. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Both Vendor A and Vendor B are now preferred for Part X"},{"id":"b","text":"Vendor B's Preferred flag is automatically cleared — at most one vendor-part per part can be Preferred","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The system blocks the change until you manually unset Vendor B"},{"id":"d","text":"Part X is removed from Vendor B's catalog entirely"}],"explanation":"There is a hard invariant: at most one vendor-part per Part may be Preferred at a time. Setting Preferred on Vendor A automatically clears it on every other vendor for that part (including Vendor B), so the 'preferred source' question always has exactly one answer. Vendor B keeps the part in its catalog — only the Preferred flag moves."},{"id":"vc5","text":"A vendor-part has price tiers of $2.00 at min qty 1, $1.60 at min qty 100, and $1.35 at min qty 500. What unit price applies to an order of 250 units?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"$2.00 — the base tier always applies"},{"id":"b","text":"$1.60 — the qty-100 tier wins because 100 ≤ 250 < 500","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"$1.35 — the lowest available price always applies"},{"id":"d","text":"An average of the three tiers"}],"explanation":"Price resolution picks the tier with the highest Min Quantity that is still ≤ the requested quantity. For 250 units, the qty-100 tier ($1.60) wins because 100 ≤ 250 but the qty-500 tier isn't reached. Order 1,000 and the qty-500 tier ($1.35) would win."},{"id":"vc6","text":"You need to onboard a distributor's full catalog of parts they supply, with vendor part numbers and lead times. What's the most efficient way?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Add each part one at a time with the + Add button"},{"id":"b","text":"Use the Import button on the Catalog tab: download the template, fill the CSV, then review the Add/Update/Error preview and Apply","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Enter all the parts during the Supply Items step of the guided wizard"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a purchase order — receiving will auto-create the vendor-parts"}],"explanation":"The Catalog tab's Import button handles bulk onboarding. Download the template for the exact columns, fill the CSV, and the two-state dialog shows a preview tagging each row Add, Update, or Error with a summary. Apply stays disabled until errors are fixed. Import matches on part number, so existing entries update rather than duplicate. The Supply Items wizard step is just a pointer to do this on the Catalog tab afterward."},{"id":"vc7","text":"Why are price tiers added-and-superseded (with effective dates) rather than edited in place, and where do you review past pricing?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They aren't — editing a tier overwrites the price with no record kept"},{"id":"b","text":"To preserve price history; you review it via the history (clock) action which opens the Price Tier History","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Because tiers are read-only once a PO is placed"},{"id":"d","text":"Price history lives only in QuickBooks after a sync"}],"explanation":"Tiers are append-and-supersede so the record of what you actually paid is preserved — you add a new tier (often with a future Effective From) instead of overwriting. The history (clock) action on a catalog row opens the Price Tier History change log. This preserved history feeds the scorecard's average price-variance calculation."}]}"""
