            AppRoutes = """["/vendors"]""",
            Tags = """["vendors","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Off-Tier Price Warnings\n\nWhen a purchase-order line is priced far from the vendor's current price tier, purchasing warns you that it's **off-tier**. How far is \"too far\" is set at one of three levels, in order:\n\n1. **This vendor's own setting** — you can set an allowed variance percent on the vendor. When it's set, it wins.\n2. **The system-wide setting** — used when the vendor doesn't have its own.\n3. **A built-in default of 5%** — used when neither is set.\n\nFor each line, the system compares the price you entered against the matching tier price and flags the line when the difference is bigger than the allowed percent. A couple of edge cases: if the tier price is zero, any non-zero price counts as off-tier; and if the part has no price on file for this vendor yet, the line is treated as off-tier so the prompt can offer to add the first price. The same check also powers the AI price-override review, which rates the risk as Low, Medium, or High (over 25% difference is High).\n\n## Vendor Performance Comparison Report\n\nThe performance report ranks all your **active** vendors side by side for a date range. Each vendor gets one row showing its on-time percent, quality percent, total spend, overall score, grade, and a trend arrow. By default it covers the last 12 months. **Trend** compares this period's score against the previous period of the same length; if there's no earlier score to compare against, no trend is shown. Vendors are listed best score first — a leaderboard. It's the all-vendors counterpart to the single-vendor Scorecard tab.\n\n## Completeness Indicator\n\nThe top of a vendor's details shows a small completeness indicator. It tells you whether the vendor has all the information the features you've turned on expect:\n\n- **Green \"Ready\"** — the vendor has everything the enabled features ask for (also what you see when nothing extra is required).\n- **Amber \"Incomplete for N\"** — at least one feature is missing something; click it to see exactly which fields are missing (for example \"Tax ID\" or \"Payment Terms\").\n\nCompleteness is about what your enabled features expect, not a hard rule — a vendor can be perfectly usable and still show \"Incomplete for N\" if a feature you turned on wants fields this vendor hasn't filled in. If the check can't run, the indicator simply shows nothing rather than a misleading \"Ready\".\n\n## Import File Format & Errors\n\nThe Catalog **Import** works in two steps. The columns (available from the Download-template link) are: part number, vendor part number, manufacturer name, vendor's manufacturer part number, lead time in days, minimum order quantity, pack size, country of origin, HTS code, and notes. How it goes:\n\n1. **Pick a file** — drag in or browse for a spreadsheet file.\n2. **Preview** — each row is marked **Add**, **Update**, or **Error**, with a running count. Rows are matched by part number against what the vendor already lists, so a part it already has becomes an **Update** (not a duplicate) and a new one becomes an **Add**.\n\nRows with a problem are marked **Error** with a message; the **Apply** button stays grayed out until every error is fixed — correct the file and re-import. Apply saves all the adds and updates at once.\n\n## Is-Manufacturer Setting\n\nOn the catalog form, the **Is Manufacturer** switch says what the vendor's role is for that part:\n\n- **On** — the vendor *is* the manufacturer. The manufacturer is the vendor, and you enter a single part number.\n- **Off (distributor)** — the vendor resells someone else's part. You record both the **vendor's part number** and the **original manufacturer's part number**. That manufacturer part number is separate from the part's own engineering part number in your catalog.\n\nThe switch changes which fields the form asks for, keeping made-by-the-vendor and resold parts clear and unambiguous.\n\n## One Preferred Source Per Part\n\nA part can have only **one preferred source at a time**. Marking a vendor as preferred for a part automatically clears the preferred mark on every other vendor for that same part — so \"the preferred source\" always has exactly one answer. The change is recorded in the activity log when it moves.\n\nThe preferred vendor's lead time, minimum order quantity, and pack size are the ones reordering and auto-generated purchase orders use. In the catalog list, the preferred row shows a filled star you can toggle directly. When a part has just one source, it's shown as a single card rather than a multi-row table.\n\n## Draft Auto-Save\n\nThe vendor form saves your work as you go. If you have unsaved changes and get logged out, crash, or your session times out, they're kept and offered back to you — both right after you log back in and as a banner on the form itself. A draft goes away only when you discard it on purpose, when you save successfully, or after it ages out. The guided wizard doesn't use this draft feature — it saves each step as you go and lets you return to a half-finished setup by reopening its page.","sections":[]}"""
